com.wm.xmldata

Class XmlDataIteratorTag

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.wm.xmldata.XmlDataTag
      • com.wm.xmldata.XmlDataContentTag
        • com.wm.xmldata.XmlDataIteratorTag
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.Cloneable

    public class XmlDataIteratorTag
extends XmlDataContentTag
    The XmlDataIteratorTag class constructs an XmlData iterator-tag from its only constituent part, which is just an ncName. It may also be used to parse an iterator-tag into its component part, which is just an ncName. Iterator-tags must begin with the ! character. There is a methods that return the full-name which consists of just the ncName. Iterator-tags are used only in copy-paths, they never appear in infosets.

    It's format is: 

     
     !ncName
    In a copy-path, iterator-tags can be used in content-tags in place of indexes, full-names, and indirect-qualifiers. The XmlCDataCopy class performs a copy operation by stepping through the range of values represented by the iterator in the source, and using the range of values in the destination. When used for an index, the iterator is an index-iterator and takes on numeric values between 0 and the size of the input array minus 1. When used in place of a full-name, the iterator is a name-iterator and takes on String values corresponding to the names of the content-tags. When used in place of an indirect-qualifier, they take on the value-tag associated with the source item. For example: 
         /items/!child    iterates ovr all of the child content-tags of item and assigns the names to the !child iterator.
     /names[!x]       iterates over all of the indexes for a repeating value
     /*any{!tag}      assigns the value-tag of the *any particle to the !tag iterator

    • Method Detail

      • createFromPath

        public static XmlDataIteratorTag createFromPath(java.lang.String name,
                                                XmlNamespaceMap nsDecls)
        Create an XmlDataIteratorTag from its String representation. Its form is !name[index]{indirectQualifier}
        where:
        • name - the symbolic name; an arbitrary alphanumeric String that must begin with the ! character
        • index -- the value index (starting at 0) or a symbolic iterator. The index iterator itself must not not have an index or qualifier
        • indirectQualifier -- is the indirect-item value tag or an iterator-tag. The qualifier iterator must itself not have an index or qualifier
        The index and qualifier never appear in the instance infoset; they are used only in the tag to provide additional information to methods. There is no default for index or qualifier; when not specified, such tags are unindexed and unqualified. If a namespace map is provided, prefixes in indirect-qualifiers are translated into fully-qualified names Examples: 
             !name
     !name[3]
     {1}*any[!x]{!qual}
        Parameters:
        name - the iterator String representation
        nsDecls - an XmlNamespaceMap
        Returns:
        an XmlDataIteratorTag

      • createFromPath

        public static XmlDataIteratorTag createFromPath(java.lang.String name)
        Creates an XmlDtaIteratorTag without using namespace declarations. Generally, they are not needed sincle itera2tor tags are symbolic place-holder rather than actual instance tags. However, namespace declarations may be needed when using an indirect-qualifer. Otherwise, this constructor uses the same form as the namespace-qualified form of createFromPath(String, XmlNamespaceMap)
        Parameters:

        Returns:
        the constructed iterator-tag.
